<br>
Sin, in and of itself, is considered going against the Will of God.  It can take many forms, from adultery to suicide, with the worst one being to associate partners with God.  &quot;Partners&quot; is kind of a loose term, not limted to actual idols or other gods, but also anything that you might put before God, such as money or sex or anything else.  If these things become more important to you than keeping to the religion, then they have become your &quot;gods&quot; so to speak.<br>
<br>
Now that I think about it, rather than focusing on sin, we focus more on personal responsibility, for all actions and all words.  You have to consider carefully what you do, and what impact that could have down the road.<br>
<br>
...and since, in Islam, government goes hand-in-hand with religion, some things that are considered sins are crimes as well, which brings you back to the Shari'ah, and the system of punishment for things that, in other traditions/societies, would be seen as sins, but not crimes.<br>
<br>
HTH<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/5/03 10:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Shari'ah</span><hr size=1> Kate-&quot;...and since, in Islam, government goes hand-in-hand with religion, some things that are considered sins are crimes as well, which brings you back to the Shari'ah, and the system of punishment for things that, in other traditions/societies, would be seen as sins, but not crimes.&quot;<br>
