<br>
I totally believe in the Shari'ah.  Anyone who is truly a Muslim must not only believe in the Shari'ah, but prefer it to any other system of government.  It's not very fashionable to say so these days, and most &quot;moderate&quot; Muslims would probably disagree, but facts are facts, and there it is.<br>
<br>
It would follow that I agree with the Hadd punishments(those that lop off body parts) when they are applied correctly and in the proper context and environment; however this is just the smallest aspect of Shari'ah, but unfortunately the one that grabs the most headlines, and the one that is abused the most.<br>
<br>
What has happened in recent years is nothing short of a travesty, and is as far from what the Shari'ah requires as can be.  It's just so typical, some guys take over the government somewhere, and the first thing they do is start with all these anti-women acts, and frighteningly there are other extremists throughout the world who think this is great.  I think it's disgusting.  There's no knowledge here, no wisdom, no justice, just blood lust and a freakish preoccupation with oppressing women.  <br>
<br>
I'm not an Islamic jurist or Shari'ah expert or anything, but even I know that you can't just set these things up in a vaccuum, nor can you hold people accountable for things outside of a bonafide Islamic society.<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 71<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/5/03 9:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Muslims worldwide</span><hr size=1> Kate this is so intersesting to me as I was listening to a guy on BookTV the other day who has travelled and studied Islam a great deal and he was pointing out the differences between the Islamic societies and Muslims we don't hear alot about outside the US, like those in India, Turkey, and other parts of Asia. His basic argument was that US involvement or interference is slowing or stopping the natural progression of the more closed societies like Iraq and the former Afghanistan so they cannot become democracies like India where Muslims can have free and open debate and take their religion into the next century. <br>
