<br>
I think the societies there are becoming very polarized, and something is going to have to break.  The problem with the participation of the US over there, is that they naturally put forth their own model as the ideal, and advertantly or inadvertantly deride the culture there as backward, lower, less, etc.  So the people are torn, they want to have good lives like Americans, but they want to keep their own cultures at the same time.  You get some people on either extreme, those who reject their indigenous culture, and those who reject American culture, but the vast majority seesaws between the two, depending.<br>
<br>
I think the issue of women's role in society is a perfect example.  In some Muslim countries, women are certainly oppressed, brutalized, etc.  This has no place in Islam, and is soundly condemned by every scholar, past and present.  So the question is what will be the most effective remedy?  To impose a new world outlook courtesy of &quot;The West&quot;, or to call the people to return to what their own faith really requires of them?  Which would be easier?  Which more effective?  If we were to send someone over there to talk about women's rights, would it be more effective to send the president of NOW, or to send an American shaikah (fem of &quot;Shaikh&quot;), someone well-versed in Islamic law?<br>
<br>
Just some thoughts...<br>
<br>
