br>
<br>
Regarding my Satanic friends, they are members of the<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.churchofsatan.com/home.html" target="top"> church of satan</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> based on the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0380015390/qid=1041967097/sr=2-1/ref=sr_2_1/002-8224533-4200024" target="top">satanic bible</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> written by Anton LeVay in 1967.  Essentially they are a group of atheists who believe strongly in personal responsibility, meritocracy, and wearing black.  They believe in the psychological power of witchcraft in that coming home from a bad day of work and stabbing a voodoo doll of your boss is therapeutic but not that your boss will feel the pain or start bleeding out his eyes.  Their high holy days a 1) Your Birthday, 2) the MONTH of halloween, and the standard equinox/solstice days.  They feel the worst sin is ignorance (knowledge is power) and they have a very entertaining <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.personalsatan.com/lttd/ubbthreads.php" target="top">bulletin board</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> that (if you sign on as a member) has some great reviews of books, art and philosophy (not available unless you sign in.)<br>
<br>
<br>
brainwashing: 1 : a forcible indoctrination to induce someone to give up basic political, social, or religious beliefs and attitudes and to accept contrasting regimented ideas<br>
2 : persuasion by propaganda or salesmanship<br>
<br>
I think this fits quite well.  We are all born atheists otherwise you wouldn’t need to teach these innocents the story of god, would you?  Therefore you are indoctrinating these children to give up their natural atheism and accept your contrasting regimented ideas about the supernatural.  It is forcible because they are not permitted to escape it.  If they ask their primary sources of information (parents) they are not provided logical secular answers and they are never informed (at least not until they are firmly programmed) that there are alternatives.  Otherwise, the alternatives are marketed in a lesser degree so as to make the one you are programming them with appear most desirable.  This is a function of the system, not the parent.  You do what the church tells you to ensure your child’s spiritual safety, what they tell you dates back to the dawning of the church.  The Jesuits (I think I said this before) had a saying, “Give me a child until he is 8 and I will have him for life.”  They didn’t say this as a matter of generous theology, it was a direct implication of the depth youth programming takes hold.<br>
<br>
Good definition, thanks.  I’ll have to keep that for future use.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> take what you learn and seek the truth about it. Some have found that they can't (DBC),it just isn't there for them<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I disagree with this statement.  I have found truth.  Not only have I found truth, but it is backed up by solid science, logic and reason.  Not some musty tome of political agendas that has been revised and beaten against the foreheads of humanity for a couple centuries.  I never cease to be amazed at how simplisticly people accept that in 2 centuries we have learned NOTHING more about the mythical land of heaven.  No angel feather, no footprints of god, no miracles, heck, the guy said he’d be back while people who knew him then were still alive.  The War Santa used to talk to people all the time.  Do you really think any of them are alive today?  Where is the 1,988 year old arab?  Makes Methusela look like a spring chicken.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Yep, we're all brain-washed idiots that can't think for ourselves.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Now that is just rude.  I never called you idiots.  I know many intelligent people who are still brainwashed.  You could easily think for yourselves, but you choose not to.  You can examine the contents of your breakfast cereal with a critical eye and evaluate calories, nutritional content and cost/value ratios.  Yet you examine your food more critically than you do your theology.  You do not challenge, you accept; you do not demand, you supplicate.  <br>
<br>
I would not call you a “maniacal manipulative parent” as Shirene alleges.  I would call you comfortable.  I would call the theological system manipulative.  It is structured to sustain itself.  You are loving, caring, generous people who have been misled by your parents and that same faith engine that misled them.  I respect everyone’s right to believe, but I do not think those beliefs have equal merit even if those people have equal right to hold them.  There are people in the world that would rather let their child die than have a tumor surgically removed.  They have a right to their faith; I have a right not to respect that decision.  <br>
<br>
You want a list of the merits of atheists?  They have many as a group that far exceed those of other demographics.  However, I don’t think that is pertinent to this discussion.  Specifically, I don’t think it is pertinent to you or I because at the root, we are loving parents that want the absolute best for our children.  As a population they list off better, we can just as easily rotate criteria until we find ones not itemized (and thus indefensible) or possibly even ones that are worse for them (though I must admit, I have not found any yet.)  <br>
<br>
Try and think of it this way.  I had cancer, and I survived it.  I broke free of the deadly killer.  I was not lucky and born into a cancer free environment.  My parents lived at a time when they didn’t know that smoking around an infant was bad or what it would do to them for long term health.  Should I not be proud of overcoming such a terrible thing?  Should I not tell those who still chain smoke and blow it into their child’s face?  Now replace all the words cancer and smoke with faith and religion, and you’ll understand.<br>
<br>
In Truth.<br>
